A ground search continued overnight on Sunday and expanded to include more than 100 members of Virginia law enforcement near the boy's home in Pulaski County, according to WDBJ.

The FBI and Virginia State Police have become involved in the search. 

Police and more than 100 volunteers who signed up to look for Noah in the small town have covered about 3.3 square miles.

Pulaski County Sheriff Jim Davis said that authorities have no evidence of foul play in his disappearance.

Investigators said search dogs stopped near the road near Noah's house, which is 'never typical'. 

No suspicious vehicles were seen in the area. 

The boy, who helped drop his mother and infant sibling drop his father off at work at 7am, is believed to be wearing a camouflage jacket, black and yellow paints and Spider-Man boots.

He may also be wearing a San Diego Chargers jersey with the number 21 on it. 

Crews have used helicopters in the search in the area, which is mostly residential with farmland and a woods by the boy's house.

