More than 100 people in the rural Virginia town signed up to search for the boy on Monday. 

They plan to continue searching for the boy round-the-clock.

Billy Chrimes, deputy search and rescue coordinator with the Virginia Department of Emergency Management, said that the best opportunity to find a missing child is often at night when they stop moving. 

Lack of food and water and potential problems with wildlife are also concerns, he told the Roanoke Times.

